properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Early-season snow for part of the Alaska highway. An unseasonably cold Arctic airmass will descend upon Yukon and northern BC beginning Saturday. Rain near the Yukon-B.C. border will likely become mixed with snow beginning Saturday evening as temperatures approach the freezing mark. The potential for wet snow will persist until midday Monday. Snowfall accumulations are possible, particularly along the highest sections of the Alaska highway between Fort Nelson and Watson Lake including near Summit Pass. The highest likelihood of accumulating snow will be overnight Saturday into Sunday morning when road surface temperatures approach zero degrees Celsius. Temperatures will return to seasonal values beginning on Tuesday. Motorists should be prepared for the potential of snow and slippery road conditions and are encouraged to check road conditions on DriveBC and www.511yukon.ca before heading out. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.

properties.Title: Severe Thunderstorm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: At 3:52 p.m. CST, Environment Canada meteorologists are tracking a severe thunderstorm capable of producing very strong wind gusts, up to nickel size hail and heavy rain. A thunderstorm with the potential to produce large hail and locally torrential downpours is 20 km east of Melville near Highway 15 and moving toward Churchbridge. ### Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Large hail can damage property and cause injury. Strong wind gusts can toss loose objects, damage weak buildings, break branches off trees and overturn large vehicles. Intense lightning is likely with any thunderstorm that develops. Remember, severe thunderstorms can produce tornadoes.

properties.Title: Special Air Quality Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Smoke is causing poor air quality and reducing visibility. Smoke is expected or occurring. A Smoky Skies Bulletin has been issued for Atlin as smoke from wildfires is impacting or likely to impact the region. ### Individuals may experience symptoms such as increased coughing, throat irritation, headaches or shortness of breath. Children, seniors, and those with cardiovascular or lung disease, such as asthma, are especially at risk. For more information on current air quality, visit www2.gov.bc.ca/gov/content/environment/air-land-water/air. Visit www.airhealth.ca for information on how to reduce your health risk and your personal contribution to pollution levels, as well as for current and forecast AQHI values. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain, at times heavy, continues. A low pressure system continues to bring heavy rain to parts of northeastern Alberta and northwestern Saskatchewan. In total, rainfall amounts of 40 to 60 mm are expected, with locally higher amounts up to 90 mm possible. This system will exit the province of Alberta by Saturday morning, bringing an end to the rain. Periods of rain are expected to linger across northern Saskatchewan until Sunday morning. ### Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Rainfall warnings are issued when significant rainfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.
